Interrelationships of Three Year Average State Poverty Rates: 2020 - 2022

(Population as of March of the following year. Rates and margins of error in percentage points. The symbol "+" indicates that the poverty rate is statistically greater at the 90 percent level of confidence, while a  "-" indicates a statistically siginificant lower rate. A blank indicates no statistically significant difference between the two states. Information on confidentiality protection, sampling error, nonsampling error, and definitions is available at <https://www2.census.gov/programs-surveys/cps/techdocs/cpsmar23.pdf>)

1 A margin of error (MOE) is a measure of an estimate's variability. The larger the MOE in relation to the size of the estimate, the less reliable the estimate. This number, when added to and subtracted from the estimate, forms the 90 percent confidence interval. MOEs shown in this table are based on standard errors calculated using replicate weights.
Source: U.S. Census Bureau, Current Population Survey, 2021 to 2023 Annual Social and Economic Supplements (CPS ASEC).
